{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628740"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:00:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:00:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17236"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17236"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9926"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77600"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9926"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17236"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63113"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"7614"},{"type":"tags","id":"10715"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23274"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23279"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77600"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDNA replication must be highly accurate to maintain genetic stability across cell divisions. Multiple mechanisms exist to ensure faithful DNA replication and repair of errors.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism for correcting mismatched nucleotides during DNA synthesis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Repairs DNA breaks via end joining","Removes damaged bases via glycosylase","Excises thymine dimers via endonuclease","Repairs breaks via sister chromatid exchange","Removes mismatches via 3\u0027 exonuclease"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eremoves mismatches via 3\u0027 exonuclease\u003C/strong\u003E (proofreading) is the primary mechanism for correcting nucleotide mismatches during DNA replication. When DNA polymerase detects a mismatched base pair, it moves backwards and removes the incorrect nucleotide before continuing with replication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf errors escape the proofreading mechanism, various secondary mismatch repair systems can identify and fix remaining base pair errors after replication is complete. Together these mechanisms maintain a very low error rate during DNA replication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent different DNA repair pathways:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepairs DNA breaks via end joining\u003C/strong\u003E (non-homologous end joining) directly rejoins broken DNA ends without a template\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemoves damaged bases via glycosylase\u003C/strong\u003E (base excision repair) primarily repairs damaged bases from oxidation, deamination, or alkylation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcises thymine dimers via endonuclease\u003C/strong\u003E (nucleotide excision repair) removes bulky DNA lesions like those caused by UV damage\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepairs breaks via sister chromatid exchange\u003C/strong\u003E (homologous recombination) repairs double-strand breaks using a sister chromatid as a template\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["DNA polymerase has an error rate of approximately 1 in 10^7 nucleotides during DNA replication.","Proofreading activity (3\u0027 to 5\u0027 exonuclease) allows DNA polymerase to detect and correct mismatched base pairs during replication.","Mismatch repair systems can identify and fix base pair errors that escape proofreading during DNA replication."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63113"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17236"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63113"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T20:18:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T20:19:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9926"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77600"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4940"},"